{{Lunisolar November|qq=}} '''Lunisolar November''' (旧暦十一月) is the eleventh {{ill|Month (Calendar)|ja|月 (暦)|lt=Month|lt_ja=月|qq=|qq=draft}} of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire|qq=|qq=draft}}).
The month that includes the {{ill|Winter Solstice|ja|冬至|qq=|qq=draft}} becomes November. In the {{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦|1=New Calendar (Japan)|lt=New Calendar|qq=|qq=draft}}, it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|November|ja|11月|qq=|qq=draft}} to early {{ill|January|ja|1月|qq=|qq=draft}}.
Another name for November is {{nihongo|'''Shimozuki'''|しもつき|qq=}}. The origin of the name is explained in [[#Etymology of traditional Japanese name]]{{efn|November|ja|11月|qq=|qq=draft}}. An alternative name is “Chūtō (仲冬)”.
In the Eastern lunisolar calendar, because the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小|qq=|qq=draft}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies by year, there are years when November ends on the 29th and no November 30th exists.
==Etymology of traditional Japanese name== {{afc comment|1=content here taken from [[:ja:11月]][[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:44, 11 May 2025 (UTC)}} In {{ill|Japan|ja|日本}}, the {{ill|November (Lunisolar)|ja|11月 (旧暦)|lt=Lunar November|lt_ja=旧暦11月}} is called '''Shimotsuki''' (しもつき), and today it is also used as an alternate name for November of the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|新暦}}. {{ill|Shimotsuki|ja|霜月}} literally means “frost month,” when frost descends. Other theories hold that it is an abbreviation of “Oshimono-zuki” (食物月; おしものづき), “food month”; or a corruption of “Shibomutsuki” (凋む月; しぼむつき) or “Suetsutsuki” (末つ月; すえつつき). Alternate names include “Kagurazuki” (神楽月; かぐらづき) and “Nezuki” (子月; ねづき).
In the Asahikawa dialect of the {{ill|Hokkaido Ainu language|ja|北海道アイヌ語}}, November is called “Nitek Rankechup” (ニテㇰランケチュㇷ゚; {{ill|Ainu language|ja|アイヌ語}}: nitek ranke cup), meaning “month of dropping tree branches.”<ref>{{Cite web |author=高橋 靖以 |url=https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html |title=月刊シロㇿ 10月号（2015.10） |website=ainugo.nam.go.jp |publisher=[[ウポポイ|国立アイヌ民俗博物館]] |language=ja |date=2015-10 |accessdate=2025-03-02 |archiveurl=https://megalodon.jp/2025-0302-0131-45/https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html |archivedate=2025-03-02 |url-status=live}}</ref>
In English, the month name {{lang|en|November}} derives from the Latin {{lang|la|novem}}, meaning “nine.” The numerical mismatch arises because the pre-46 BCE Roman calendar began in March, making November the ninth month.
November begins on the same {{ill|day of the week|ja|曜日|1=Day of the week|2=ja|3=曜日|qq=}} as {{ill|March|ja|3月}} of that year, and in common years also the same as {{ill|February|ja|2月}}.
