{{Lunisolar November|qq=}} '''Lunisolar November''' (旧暦十一月) is the eleventh [[:en:Month|Month]] of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=}} ([[:en:Lunisolar calendar|Lunisolar calendar]]).
The month that includes the [[:en:Winter solstice|Winter Solstice]] becomes November. In the {{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦|1=New Calendar (Japan)|lt=New Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar (Japan)|qq=}}, it corresponds approximately to late [[:en:November|November]] to early [[:en:January|January]].
Another name for November is {{nihongo|'''Shimozuki'''|しもつき|qq=}}. The origin of the name is explained in [[#Etymology of traditional Japanese name]]{{efn|November|ja|11月|qq=|qq=draft}}. An alternative name is “Chūtō (仲冬)”.
In the Eastern lunisolar calendar, because the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小|qq=|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Large and Small|qq=}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies by year, there are years when November ends on the 29th and no November 30th exists.
==Etymology of traditional Japanese name== {{afc comment|1=content here taken from [[:ja:11月]][[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:44, 11 May 2025 (UTC)}} In [[:en:Japan|Japan]], the {{ill|November (Lunisolar)|ja|11月 (旧暦)|lt=Lunar November|lt_ja=旧暦11月|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/November (Lunisolar)|qq=}} is called '''Shimotsuki''' (しもつき), and today it is also used as an alternate name for November of the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|新暦|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian calendar|qq=}}. {{ill|Shimotsuki|ja|霜月|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuki|qq=}} literally means “frost month,” when frost descends. Other theories hold that it is an abbreviation of “Oshimono-zuki” (食物月; おしものづき), “food month”; or a corruption of “Shibomutsuki” (凋む月; しぼむつき) or “Suetsutsuki” (末つ月; すえつつき). Alternate names include “Kagurazuki” (神楽月; かぐらづき) and “Nezuki” (子月; ねづき).
In the Asahikawa dialect of the [[:en:Ainu language|Hokkaido Ainu language]], November is called “Nitek Rankechup” (ニテㇰランケチュㇷ゚; [[:en:Ainu language|Ainu language]]: nitek ranke cup), meaning “month of dropping tree branches.”<ref>{{Cite web |author=高橋 靖以 |url=https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html |title=月刊シロㇿ 10月号（2015.10） |website=ainugo.nam.go.jp |publisher=[[ウポポイ|国立アイヌ民俗博物館]] |language=ja |date=2015-10 |accessdate=2025-03-02 |archiveurl=https://megalodon.jp/2025-0302-0131-45/https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html |archivedate=2025-03-02 |url-status=live}}</ref>
In English, the month name {{lang|en|November}} derives from the Latin {{lang|la|novem}}, meaning “nine.” The numerical mismatch arises because the pre-46 BCE Roman calendar began in March, making November the ninth month.
November begins on the same [[:en:Day of the week|day of the week]] as [[:en:March|March]] of that year, and in common years also the same as [[:en:February|February]].
